  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Celebrating the New Year
  author: Lee Duk-wu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    As the celestial measure shifts and the first spring arrives anew,
    The wooden bell rings forth its message, gathering every blessing.

    Your Majesty, in this New Year's greeting:
    Your wisdom flows serene and boundless,
    Your virtue encompasses all under heaven.
    In governing the world and nurturing the people,
    The four quarters bow in willing submission.
    Following the seasons, you dispense instruction,
    And ten thousand things find peace and harmony.

    With this auspicious moment of the first month,
    Your sacred virtue shines ever brighter.
    Though your servant's duties bind me to distant fields,
    Unable to attend the daily court,
    My heart turns ever toward the steps of heaven,
    Holding but one prayer:
    That your celestial years extend long as the heavens themselves.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'wooden bell' (木鐸) was an ancient Chinese instrument used to herald important proclamations and teachings.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'celestial measure' (玉衡) refers to the Jade Transversal star, one of the stars in the Big Dipper, symbolizing the regulation of the seasons and cosmic order.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'steps of heaven' (蓂階) is a poetic reference to the royal court, suggesting both its celestial authority and its distance from the author.
